Overview

This project documents the design and implementation of a cloud-based Security Information and Event Management (SIEM) lab built using Microsoft Sentinel and Azure Log Analytics.

The objective was to simulate a practical security monitoring environment in which an internet-facing virtual machine generated real-world authentication telemetry that could be collected, analyzed, and converted into actionable security detections.

During the observation period, the exposed honeypot environment recorded more than 52,000 authentication attempts within approximately 30 minutes, demonstrating the volume of automated scanning and credential-based attacks continuously targeting publicly accessible systems.

The project focuses on:

Centralized security log collection
Authentication and network telemetry analysis
KQL-based threat hunting
Detection engineering
Microsoft Sentinel analytics rules
MITRE ATT&CK mapping
Incident investigation
SIEM architecture and data flow

Disclaimer: This project was conducted in a controlled Azure lab environment using infrastructure owned and managed by the author. No unauthorized systems were accessed or tested.
